  "opinion": "As a woman who’s spent most of her life in the trades and construction fields, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotypes can shape people’s confidence. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a term from academic papers—it’s the quiet fear that shows up when someone feels their identity might undermine their ability to succeed. For me, it’s the moment a young girl hesitates to ask a question in a science class because she’s worried she’ll be labeled 'not smart enough.' It’s the way I’ve heard men in my shop say, 'I’m not good at math,' even when they’ve built houses for decades. This isn’t about labeling—it’s about the weight of expectation that makes people doubt themselves before they even try. I believe we must address this because it’s not just a problem for girls or minorities; it’s a problem for everyone who feels they don’t belong. What we need is simple, practical change: teachers and mentors who see students as people first, not just data points. In my community, I’ve started volunteering at local workshops where we focus on hands-on projects that show STEM isn’t just for the classroom—it’s for building real things, like bridges and homes. When students see their own skills being valued, the fear fades. Addressing stereotype threat isn’t about fixing people—it’s about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to try. It’s about remembering that the best builders aren’t just those who know the right answers, but those who dare to ask questions.",
